        package "badexample" {
            class Rectangle <<C>> {
                + height : int
                + width : int

                - area() 

                # getHeight():int
                # getWidth():int
                ^ setHeight(int) void
                ^ setWidth(int) void
            }

            class Square <<C>>{
                 ^setHeight(int):void;
                  ^setWidth(int):void;  
             }   

              note right of 10#Rectangle::areaShouldBeCalculatedCorrectlyWithDerivedClassSquare();\n\nArea should be calculated correctly using derived classes like squares.\nIt ensures correct behavior even if we use subclasses instead base ones directly! \nTo achieve this goal let us create another method named 'calculate_area' which will calculate areas based on given dimensions regardless whether they belong to rectangles or their subtypes such as Squares etc.. This way our program becomes more flexible because now users can pass any object whose type inherits from Shape without worrying about what specific kind shape was passed into function call since all shapes share common properties i.e., having both length & breadth so calculating total surface covered by them would always yield same result irrespective how many sides does each individual figure possess!\nSo here goes nothing...\nclass Test{\ntest_case_1(){assert_equal(4,square.calculate());} //test case where input parameter represents square instance returns expected output value equal four units squared due fact there are two pairs parallel lines forming closed loop around center point thus making up whole perimeter consisting exactly eight segments long altogether hence dividing half gives answer sought after namely twice product side lengths multiplied together yielding final count representing entire enclosed region bounded within outermost boundary formed connecting endpoints adjacent vertices consecutively until reaching back original position again completing full circuit once before stopping execution flow entirely leaving behind computed numerical representation describing geometric configuration described above... }\n}\nendnote

